Paul Simon: 'God's not into pop - he likes gospel'
At 69, Paul Simon is about to release a new album full of big issues and jokes, he tells Neil McCormick
.
By Neil McCormick
6:48PM BST 25 May 2011
Follow Comments
In an unassuming rehearsal room in a small Connecticut town, Paul Simon sits facing into a circle of a dozen musicians, sound technicians and roadies, issuing soft-spoken instructions. “It’s just on the verge of being really great,” he says, thick, strong arms resting on a guitar perched across his midriff as he makes detailed comments regarding parts his band should play. “I like the talking drum, but maybe it should talk a little less.” The groove starts up again, and Simon joins in. With his pale, round face, thin flyaway hair pasted across a balding pate, he looks all of his 69 years, but he sings with a soft, pure tone undiminished by age, and as the music gathers momentum, a big grin spreads, and the years fall away. “I love to make music,” Simon tells me later. “I love it when the rhythm is right, when the sound is really what I want, when the parts fit together so intimately, it feels natural and you give yourself over to the pulse and excitement.” He is, he admits, a demanding band leader. “If it’s not quite right, it really drives me crazy. Your ear goes to the irritant. The main villain is usually clutter. It takes a lot of work to get it up to a point where it’s wrong.” His fastidiousness is impressive, but I don’t suppose you get to be one of the greatest singer-songwriters of all time without paying attention to detail. “I really think of myself as a songwriter- singer, not a singer-songwriter,” says Simon. “This is all I’ve really done my whole life, write songs, but there’s still plenty to learn, even if, at this point, I’m mostly teaching myself.” Simon is preparing for the release of his first album in five years, So Beautiful or So What (out in the UK on June 13). It’s an album that seems to bring together all kinds of strands of his musical life, the African grooves of Graceland shaded with his constant devotion to American blues, doo-wop and rock’n’roll underpinning the acoustic guitars, flowing melodies, orchestrations and beautiful harmonies of classic Simon & Garfunkel, all wrapped around the kind of philosophical, self-questioning, conversational lyrics that have been his hallmark since the solo Seventies classics such as Still Crazy After All These Years. Related Articles
Paul Simon exclusive on new album
03 Jun 2011
Paul Simon to release new single in June
25 May 2011
Paul Simon: a song for every occasion
25 May 2011
Will we still love them when they're... 70?
18 May 2011
Paul Simon's Christmas single
17 Nov 2010
Paul Simon: Major releases scheduled for 2011
17 Nov 2010
“One of the things people have attached to me is that I’m always changing, but I think I’m just evolving, shedding some things and taking others along with me. There are things that I’ve taken from the first songs that I wrote when I was 15. I like doo-wop. I stick it in all the time. I like that finger picking I learned when I lived in England. I can’t play much blues at all, but the little bit I play is slap and pushed strings that all comes from Davey Graham and Bert Jansch. A lot of things I learned about rhythm from African musicians were useful and made sense to me.” One of the things, he dropped, of course, was his partnership with Art Garfunkel, although the duo still reunite for occasional gigs. “It’s a pleasure to sing with Artie, but I don’t like it when it overwhelms what I’m doing now. We only made five albums, so when we go out we can do maybe 22 songs, and after that you’re getting into songs that you really don’t want to sing. I Am A Rock is a little on the young side. Some of them, I couldn’t be happier with. Sound of Silence is beautiful when I sing it with him, The Boxer is great, Bridge Over Troubled Water I never sing without him, so that is pleasurable, but it’s what I did 40 years ago. I don’t like the inference that what I did then is the definition of who I am.” The themes of Simon’s new album are typically grand (the value of love in hard times, the question of whether existence is just a cosmic joke, the very meaning of life) but the way they are addressed is light and spry, offering questions rather than answers, and peppered with jokes. There are a lot of appearances by God, although He is not conjured up as a particularly benign deity. Love Is the Eternal Sacred Light collapses the whole history of the universe into a couple of quite extraordinary verses, but has God commenting, “Big bang, that’s a joke I made up once when I had eons to kill”. Simon leaves God driving down a highway in an American car, flicking through radio stations for something he can bear to listen to. “God’s not into pop music,” laughs Simon. “He likes the gospel shows.” Simon concedes that “this type of metaphysical or spiritual thinking is a part of what goes on when I wander around”. Simon rose to prominence when the first great wave of post-Dylan singer-songwriters were seen as spiritual seekers, poetic voices of their generation’s higher aspirations. With his soft-spoken manner and thoughtful aura of Jewish New York intellectual, Simon seems the definition of a musical sage, yet shrugs off the notion of imparting wisdom. “When I write these songs, I don’t know what they are when I begin them. My criterion is truth. Is that what I think? Is that what I believe? It doesn’t have to be incredibly insightful, it just can’t be a lie. I’m not even crazy about making a point. I think that’s why it takes me longer now to write, because I see both sides. Most of the time I find it really interesting.” It is odd to find this most eloquent and considered of wordsmiths admitting that lyrics aren’t his songwriting priority. “It’s easier to talk about the words, but my joy out of this is the music. The words are hard. If I think something is really poorly said, I won’t stay with it, but if I think the lyric is okay, I’ll let it go. I feel like a kid let out of school. 'Alright, see you, bye!’ ” Simon lives a quiet life in Connecticut, an hour’s train ride from Manhattan but, by his own admission, cut off from the city’s energy. Married (for the third time) to singer-songwriter Edie Brickell, they have three children, and can sometimes perform together at school events, singing the Everly Brother’s All I Have to Do Is Dream (a song on which the young Simon and Garfunkel learned their harmonic trade). “It’s beautiful, our blend, I like to sing with her.” He has also written and played with his 38-year-old son Harper (from his first marriage), appearing on his acclaimed 2009 debut album. His demeanour suggests domestic contentment. At 69, with a young family, he doesn’t feel old, but hopes he will “write into old age”. He has a sense that the first generation of Sixties singer-songwriters (Dylan, Cohen, Neil Young) are on “a new frontier”, a place where songwriters have never ventured before. “My desire is just to see how far I can go. Really old age is such a foreign country. Hopefully, I’ll be able to speak from that point, and bring pleasure to people with what I observe. Although what I observe might be harsh. It might mean writing songs saying, 'What can I tell you? It stinks.’ So we’ll see. What’s the other choice? Go away? Be quiet? This is what I am, this is what I do. I make up songs and try to make them interesting. Stand back and let me get on with it.” Buy Paul Simon Tickets from Telegraph Tickets Rock and Pop Features
