Heathrow Terminal 5: 'It was a shambles as soon as doors opened'
By Gordon Rayner, Chief Reporter
11:31PM GMT 28 Mar 2008
British Airways was warned by its own staff that the move to Terminal 5 would be a fiasco because they had not been given sufficient training, it was claimed yesterday.
There were allegations that senior executives had been urged to put back the opening date, and managers were accused of being "complacent" about the possibility of major problems.
Despite months of preparations for the opening of the £4.3?billion facility, during which BA staff supposedly tested the terminal's systems to destruction, such basic and foreseeable problems as workers having trouble parking and getting through security led to a catastrophic failure of the baggage handling system.
Baggage handlers, in particular, were woefully under-prepared for the job in hand, as they were not sufficiently familiar with their new working practices or with the geography of Terminal 5 to be able to work at full tilt.
One baggage handler said yesterday: "It turned into a shambles the moment the doors opened. The staff would blame the lack of training and essential support that was promised. During the inadequate training days prior to the opening, any staff questions were bounced back with 'I don't know' and 'It will be clear on the day'."
Related Articles
Heathrow Terminal 5: BA apologises for chaos
28 Mar 2008
The anonymous worker, speaking to the BBC, added: "Staff signage is non-existent and, quite frankly, how are we expected to help customers if we are not helped first?"
Another member of Heathrow staff suggested there were too few baggage handlers to deal with the 12,000 bags per hour which can be processed by the automated baggage transfer system.
"We knew it wasn't going to work," the worker said. "It shouldn't have opened. The computers are too quick for the people - you have to have a human at the other end unloading bags."
Although Heathrow's Spanish-owned operator, BAA, was partly to blame for some of Thursday's early glitches, such as problems with a staff car park, BA's own press office said "staff familiarisation" problems had been partly to blame for the meltdown.
One industry source said: "Both sets of management at BA and BAA have been incredibly complacent about T5. You have got to put your heart and soul into a project like this and they haven't."
The airline's chief executive, Willie Walsh, said: "I am accepting responsibility for the mistakes we made. If people want someone to point the finger at then they can point it at me. Our performance was not good enough."
Although Mr Walsh, who has huge support from the City after turning around BA's fortunes by dramatically cutting costs, is unlikely to be forced out of his job at this stage, he has a tough month ahead.
He admitted yesterday that the planned transfer of all long-haul services from Terminal 4 into Terminal 5 next month was now "under review" and BA faces another test next week with the implementation of the European Union's "open skies" policy, which will undermine BA's dominance at Heathrow by allowing many more airlines to operate services to the United States.
David Wilshire, a Conservative MP whose Spelthorne constituency includes Heathrow, and who sits on the parliamentary transport committee, said it was too early to say whether Mr Walsh should go.
"This has been an utter disaster but it still isn't clear exactly who is to blame," said Mr Wilshire. "We keep hearing stories about car parking problems, lifts not working, and security clearance logjams - all of which are BAA's fault - so I think we have to wait to find out whether Mr Walsh is being a gentleman by accepting the blame or whether it really was his fault."
