The £40 million clean up of St Paul’s Cathedral Wren’s masterpiece, which is 300 years old, has been restored to its full glory, finds Iain Hollingshead . Link to this video
By Iain Hollingshead
7:00AM BST 21 Jun 2011
Comments
“The God who made the world and everything in it is the Lord of heaven and earth and does not live in temples built by hands.”
One can see what the author of the Acts of the Apostles was getting at, but perhaps he’d change his tune if he visited St Paul’s today. In a service this morning attended by the Queen the cathedral is celebrating not only its 300th anniversary, but also the fact that, for the first time in 15 years, it is entirely free from scaffolding.
The cathedral’s restoration – the first comprehensive works, both inside and out, in its illustrious history – cost £40 million and has taken almost half as long as it did Wren to design and build it. The result, however, is nigh-on miraculous. Inside the light floods in from the heavens, falling on freshly scrubbed carvings and sculptures. The Portland stone exterior gleams once more; the ravages of three centuries of pollution, wind and rain a distant memory. Even the office workers lunching on the steps facing Fleet Street take occasional admiring glances at the newly naked west front.
“I used to think it was rather more like a railway station than a great cathedral,” says Martin Stancliffe, the wonderfully titled Surveyor to the Fabric, who has overseen the project. “It was very dirty, very unkempt. And that made it a very gloomy, very disappointing building to work with. I think it’s not unfair to say it has been a transformation.”
Transforming the “temple” that has witnessed the funerals of Nelson, the Duke of Wellington and Churchill, the peace services for the end of both world wars, and the marriage of Prince Charles and Diana, Princess of Wales, has certainly required many hands. And perhaps most hands-on of these are the stonemasons, all of whom have been invited to today’s service. If anyone deserves to celebrate the end of the cathedral’s makeover – perhaps with a reading from Psalm 84, “How lovely is your dwelling place” – it is they.
When the Telegraph visited last week Gareth Shiels was sitting astride one remaining bar of scaffolding, “pointing” the final bits of the north wall. Pointing involves cutting out the cement joints where water has entered, and replacing them. More than 150,000 blocks have been restored in this way. How long has Shiels been doing this? “Long enough,” he answers (it turns out he’s been there since 2006). Mark Fosh, who spent three years cleaning almost one million cubic feet of stone, is similarly relieved it’s all over. “It was like being a chimpanzee at the zoo,” he jokes, rocking backwards and forwards to display his technique with a hosepipe.
The pressure had to be kept low so as not to damage the stonework. Lichen and moss build-up was widespread. Some carbon and soot deposits had to be chiselled out by hand. The south side of the cathedral, nearest the various power stations, was the worst (ironically, Wren’s rebuilding of St Paul’s after the Great Fire, the fourth cathedral on the Ludgate Hill site since 604AD, was financed by a tax on coal imports).
Not all the work, however, was mundane. Stancliffe was puzzled by an alarming horizontal crack that went right through the middle of the Thornhill dome. Eventually he concluded that it was the result of a high explosive bomb dropped on the north transept during the Second World War, the blast lifting the entire dome for a millisecond or two.
The stonemasons’ work also involved the reconstruction of the west steps and the re-covering of all the external cornices. Michael Crocker, a recently qualified apprentice, describes enthusiastically how he spent four weeks in the workshop under the cathedral renovating a balustrade that was on the verge of falling 30-odd feet to the ground. Some 25 balustrades were renovated this way. A lot of the work, however, had to be carried out in situ, high above the London skyline.
In the dome they restored a rusty structural chain that had existed since Wren’s time. Slightly lower, facing north, the statue of St Philip, which was removed 20 years ago when it became unsafe, is back in his rightful place, keeping a watchful eye on the London Stock Exchange. Up here the attention to detail is remarkable. St Philip’s back might be adorned with an ugly lightning conductor, but such practicalities aside, the cherubs at an altitude rarely glimpsed by the public are still carved with intimate intricacy. The cleaning process has revealed previously concealed details such as a solitary tear on the face of a cherub. The high-level swags show exquisite pomegranates and apricots. Today’s stonemasons are full of admiration for their predecessors – and, it has to be said, jealousy. As well as finding marbles in the stonework (for spacing, presumably), oyster shells (a common food in the 18th century) and one intact clay pipe, they also regularly came across initials, or Masons’ Marks, carved into the stonework. “We wanted to carve our own initials but were not allowed,” says Fosh.
No matter. They should take inspiration from the inscription on Wren’s tomb: “If you seek his monument, look around you.”
Today St Paul’s again holds its own on the City skyline, a reminder of matters spirtual among the towers of Mammon. “It probably looks better than at any time since its completion in 1711,” says Stancliffe. “The driving intention of the whole project has been how to make the cathedral act as the real missionary for the church – to make the building speak as clearly and as openly as it can to everybody who comes through the door.”
Inside those doors the cathedral’s annual two million visitors will find the Whispering Gallery repainted, every pipe of the organ which Mendelssohn once played cleaned, the walls washed several shades lighter and all six million pieces of a mosaic individually cleaned with cotton buds and de-ionised water.
They might even find God. “It causes everyone to pause and look around them with wonder,” says Stancliffe. “It makes all the services here much more glorious than they were before.”
