Roddy Forsyth: Craig Whyte and Rangers paying heavy price for damage done by Sir David Murray
The familiar sound which greets each fresh piece of bad news about Rangers does not come solely from gleeful Celtic fans relishing the torments of their ancient adversaries. That cackling is also the clamour of flocks of chickens flying home to roost at Ibrox. Going with the Flo: one only has to utter the name of Tore Andre Flo to conjure the limits of Rangers's folly in the transfer market Photo: REUTERS	By Roddy Forsyth
11:00PM BST 15 Sep 2011
Comments
The tax tribunal that could tip Rangers into insolvency is the legacy of an era of such profligacy that it makes the eyes water to consider how money was once lavished on the club in a vain – and the word is employed here in both its meanings – attempt to conquer Europe. No manager of a Scottish club has ever come close to Dick Advocaat’s spending on players and, as matters stand, none ever will. Advocaat laid out £80 million on players who made no impact whatsoever in European competition. Even worse, their brief period of domestic domination came to a crunching end when Martin O’Neill arrived at Celtic in 2000. The Dutchman quit as Rangers manager the following season, although his contract had two years left to run. From time to time he attempts to rewrite history, as when he said last year: “If I have a debt of £60 million but the players are worth £150 million, then I don’t have a debt – it’s like buying a house.” You got it in one there, Dick. Look what happened to people who bet large on that particular commodity. As for Rangers, we only have to utter the name of Tore Andre Flo to conjure the limits of the club’s folly in the transfer market. Related Articles
Whyte in eye of the storm
12 Sep 2011
Rangers finances are true measure of fortunes
11 Sep 2011
Dundee United 0 Rangers 1
10 Sep 2011
Financial worries continue to stalk corridors of Ibrox
09 Sep 2011
Extreme laws will not tackle the football bigots
07 Sep 2011
Rangers reject Jelavic bid
30 Aug 2011
Interesting to note that the hapless Norwegian cost the club 20 per cent of £60 million – and would have been worth what, by Advocaat’s standards or anyone else’s? However, it is not the oddly insecure and bombastic Dutch manager who compels our attention so much as the philosophy he represented. Sir David Murray’s tenure at Ibrox is encapsulated in his boast that if Celtic spent £5, he would outlay £10 and – as was pointed out in these pages when Craig Whyte assumed control of the club – Murray’s cash did bring in almost exactly twice as many trophies as Celtic over the period of his ownership. The fatal flaw in the calculation – and it is debatable how much was ever calculated – is that the honours were all domestic, a native Scottish currency that was rapidly declining in value compared to the prestige and riches to be acquired from success in the Premier League and Champions League. Even in that respect, Rangers have simply reaped what once they sowed. When David Holmes, then chairman at Ibrox, appointed Graeme Souness as manager in 1986, he unleashed wage inflation in Scotland. For a while, all the auguries were golden – at least for Rangers. With English clubs banned from Europe after the Heysel disaster, Souness pillaged the England international side for players. Ibrox had been reconstructed – largely through funds made available by Rangers Pools – in response to the 1971 Disaster and was well ahead of the game when the Taylor Report into safety at football grounds saddled almost every other club in Britain with massive bills for rebuilding. Such an immense outlay had to be clawed back somehow and, with shining new arenas projecting the image of a reformed and wholly modern sport, the Premier League was born. That, together with the unfeasibly large salaries generated by the Bosman case, meant that any Scottish club trying to compete in like style over the longer run was bound to be throttled by debt. Very few foresaw the outcome, yet the scenario had already been played out in Scotland itself. Unable to compete with Rangers on salaries or transfer fees, Aberdeen and Dundee United declined sharply from their 1980s prosperity and competitiveness. Hearts were double victims because they did, for a brief spell, try to achieve some sort of parity in spending, only to acquire a millstone of debt that exists to this day and is currently borne by Vladimir Romanov with the help of his banking interests. However, Celtic – deeply scarred by the events of 1994 when they came within minutes of bankruptcy – did learn a traumatic lesson. Although their trophy cabinet was replenished much less frequently than its Ibrox equivalent, they can bring another perspective to bear on Murray’s now notorious pronouncement. For every £1 of Celtic debt, Rangers have run up £25 – and that is not counting the worst case scenario of an adverse verdict in the HMRC tax tribunal, which could take the Old Firm debt ratio up to 1:120. As for Whyte, nobody knows how he has made his money – because he is remarkably secretive about its provenance – or how much he is worth or what his business plan promises, other than the reduction of salaries and an increased dependence on the notoriously unreliable commodity of young players. Perhaps he will have Rangers declared insolvent – when we spoke on Monday he did not refute the suggestion that the notion must have its attractions – and, if so, it is very likely that the club will endure a welter of recriminations that will make the current publicity look like a favourable advertisement. If it does come to that, though – and whatever responsibility or culpability falls upon Whyte – the serious damage was done back in the days of Advocaat, when the manager and the owner of Rangers revelled in their ability to outspend their local rivals. And – mea culpa – the media did not urge restraint because every big transfer headline sold newspapers and satellite TV subscriptions. Plus the fact, it made Scottish football look forceful, attractive and wealthy. What price that happening again? What price indeed? The day David Francey got a real mouthful
Sad as I was to learn of the passing of my old colleague, David Francey, there was a certain aptness to hearing the news while in Madrid. David’s greatest feats were accomplished on the road – he covered all three Scottish successes in European competition – Celtic in Lisbon in 1967, Rangers in Barcelona in 1972 and Aberdeen in Gothenburg in 1983 – and his modulated, old-style Scottish accent was familiar to listeners elsewhere in the UK. Mind you, it was David’s turn to get a mouthful – quite literally – when Celtic played a game in Budapest in the 1970s. Francey was installed in front of the stand with the veteran newspaperman, John Blair, later to become press officer for the Scottish Football Association. As Francey was in full flow, a mighty clearance was booted straight at him. He was working with the old-fashioned metal lip microphone (still in use) and took the full force of ball and mike in the face. As David fell backwards, dazed and disoriented, Blair gamely attempted to offer a description of the action, but was soon forced to admit that it was an acquired skill that he lacked. Happily, Francey was able to resume normal service, albeit with a swollen and bleeding lip. After the match he deserved the opportunity to retire to his hotel room to “debrief and relax” – a Francey-esque euphemism for the opportunity to uncork the miniatures of whisky he effortlessly charmed air stewardesses into slipping into his cabin bag. What are your favourite memories of David Francey?
